{"title":"Level 15 — Real-World Capstone Projects","markdown":{"headingText":"Level 15 — Real-World Capstone Projects","headingAttr":{"id":"","classes":["unnumbered"],"keyvalue":[]},"containsRefs":false,"markdown":"\n::: {.pbl-box .pbl-problem}\n**Where this level is headed**\n\nEvery earlier level taught one tool at a time, on carefully-scoped questions. Real analysis rarely arrives that neatly — a research question shows up first, and it's up to you to decide which tools from Levels 1-14 to reach for, in what order, and how to report what you find. This final level presents full, end-to-end capstone projects using this course's own dataset, each one requiring the entire pipeline: import, clean, explore, visualize, model, and report.\n:::\n\n## What this level covers\n\n- A hypertension risk-factor investigation, using logistic regression to weigh age, BMI, and smoking status together\n- A smoking and cardiovascular risk comparison, combining chi-square tests, t-tests, and effect sizes into one coherent verdict\n- A geographic patterns investigation across all five counties, combining ANOVA, visualization, and Level 10's file-automation together\n- A longitudinal blood pressure project using the multi-visit and baseline/follow-up datasets, including a real look at participant attrition\n- A reproducible, parameterized \"dashboard\" report bringing together risk modeling, geography, and longitudinal trends for any single county\n- Guidance for designing and executing your own independent capstone project, from a completely new dataset, using this same disciplined workflow\n\n::: {.pbl-box .pbl-mission}\n**A preview mission**\n\nYour mission across this level: work through five complete, real capstone projects built on this course's own data — then use everything you've learned to plan and execute an independent project of your own, from raw data to a report you'd be comfortable putting your name on.\n:::\n\n::: {.callout-note}\n## A note on scope\n\nThis level's five worked capstones (Pages 1-5) use only the datasets already built throughout this course — `participants.csv`, the multi-visit blood pressure files (Level 6, reused in Level 8 and 11), and the baseline/follow-up enrollment files (Level 6's join lessons). Physical activity, cognitive decline, and neighborhood-deprivation questions mentioned in earlier drafts of this overview would require data this course's dataset doesn't contain — Page 6 instead gives you a general-purpose template for tackling exactly those kinds of questions with a real dataset of your own choosing.\n:::\n","srcMarkdownNoYaml":""},"formats":{"html":{"identifier":{"display-name":"HTML","target-format":"html","base-format":"html"},"execute":{"fig-width":7,"fig-height":5,"fig-format":"retina","fig-dpi":96,"df-print":"default","error":false,"eval":true,"cache":null,"freeze":"auto","echo":true,"output":true,"warning":false,"include":true,"keep-md":false,"keep-ipynb":false,"ipynb":null,"enabled":null,"daemon":null,"daemon-restart":false,"debug":false,"ipynb-filters":[],"ipynb-shell-interactivity":null,"plotly-connected":true,"message":false,"engine":"markdown"},"render":{"keep-tex":false,"keep-typ":false,"keep-source":false,"keep-hidden":false,"prefer-html":false,"output-divs":true,"output-ext":"html","fig-align":"default","fig-pos":null,"fig-env":null,"code-fold":false,"code-overflow":"scroll","code-link":true,"code-line-numbers":false,"code-tools":true,"tbl-colwidths":"auto","merge-includes":true,"inline-includes":false,"preserve-yaml":false,"latex-auto-mk":true,"latex-auto-install":true,"latex-clean":true,"latex-min-runs":1,"latex-max-runs":10,"latex-makeindex":"makeindex","latex-makeindex-opts":[],"latex-tlmgr-opts":[],"latex-input-paths":[],"latex-output-dir":null,"link-external-icon":false,"link-external-newwindow":false,"self-contained-math":false,"format-resources":[],"notebook-links":true},"pandoc":{"standalone":true,"wrap":"none","default-image-extension":"png","to":"html","css":["../styles.